description:
Large Reasoning Models (LRMs) have significantly improved performance in recent years by generating long-chain reasoning, but this has also brought problems such as reasoning redundancy, computational waste, and uncontrollable reasoning paths. Existing methods (such as Self-Braking Tuning) mainly make local adjustments from the perspective of "suppressing over-reasoning," but they are essentially still in the framework of independent optimization per token or per step, ignoring the high-order dependency structure between reasoning steps.  
 &nbsp; 
  This paper proposes a novel training paradigm: Supermodular Reasoning Optimization (SRO). We introduce supermodular function optimization theory into the training of large reasoning models for the first time, modeling the complete reasoning trajectory as a set function optimization problem, in which there is a "synergy" between reasoning steps. Unlike the traditional independence assumption, we prove that high-quality reasoning essentially satisfies a structural characteristic of "increasing marginal returns," that is, the value of subsequent reasoning steps depends on the set of existing steps.  
 &nbsp; 
  Based on this, we propose three core mechanisms: (1) modeling the value of the reasoning set, (2) training signals driven by supermodular gain, and (3) a synergistic triggering reasoning generation strategy. This paradigm no longer simply shortens or lengthens inference, but instead learns "which combinations of steps are most valuable."  
 &nbsp; 
  This method fundamentally changes the training objective of LRM: shifting from "maximizing the probability of sequence generation" to "maximizing the collaborative value of the inference set," providing a theoretical basis for unifying inference efficiency and quality.

